1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:07,175
(1 John 4:16): ‘God is love, and he who dwells in love dwells in God and God in him.

2
00:00:07,125 --> 00:00:11,337
This is the epistle we read at Mass, and it is St John speaking.

3
00:00:11,337 --> 00:00:14,225
Take the opening words: ‘God is love.

4
00:00:14,225 --> 00:00:20,587
That is so, inasmuch as all that can love, all that does love, he compels by his love to love him.

5
00:00:20,587 --> 00:00:28,125
God is love, secondly, inasmuch as every God-created and loving thing compels him by its love to love it, willy-nilly.

6
00:00:28,125 --> 00:00:34,062
God is love, thirdly, inasmuch as his love drives all his lovers out of multiplicity.

7
00:00:34,062 --> 00:00:41,050
The love of God in multiplicity pursues the love which is himself right out of multiplicity into his very unity.

8
00:00:41,050 --> 00:00:48,187
God is love, fourthly, who by his love provides all creatures with their life and being, preserving them in his love.

9
00:00:48,187 --> 00:00:55,587
The colour of the cloth is preserved in the cloth: even so creatures are preserved in existence by love, that is, God.

10
00:00:55,587 --> 00:01:03,912
Take the colour from cloth, its subsistence is gone: so do creatures all lose their subsistence if taken from love, to wit, God.

11
00:01:03,912 --> 00:01:08,675
God is love, and so lovely is he that lovers all love him, willy-nilly.

12
00:01:08,675 --> 00:01:12,137
No creature is so vile as to love what is bad.

13
00:01:12,137 --> 00:01:15,450
What we love must be good or must seem to be good.

14
00:01:15,450 --> 00:01:19,925
But creaturely good, all told, is rank evil as compared with God.

15
00:01:19,925 --> 00:01:26,887
St Augustine says, ‘Love, that in meditating love thou mayst provide the wherewithal to satisfy thy soul.

16
00:01:26,887 --> 00:01:28,250
God is love.

17
00:01:28,250 --> 00:01:31,175
My children, mark me, I pray you.

18
00:01:31,175 --> 00:01:31,962
Know!

19
00:01:31,962 --> 00:01:38,300
God loves my soul so much that his very life and being depend upon his loving me, whether he would or no.

20
00:01:38,300 --> 00:01:46,687
To stop God loving me would be to rob him of his Godhood; for God is love no less than he is truth; as he is good, so is he love as well.

21
00:01:46,687 --> 00:01:49,737
It is the absolute truth, as God lives.

22
00:01:49,737 --> 00:01:56,400
There were certain theologians who maintained that the love which is within us is the Holy Ghost, but this is false.

23
00:01:56,400 --> 00:02:07,012
For the bodily food we take is changed into us, but the spiritual food we receive changes us into itself, hence love divine is not preserved in us, otherwise there would be two.

24
00:02:07,012 --> 00:02:10,825
Divine love preserves us in itself as one in the same.

25
00:02:10,825 --> 00:02:15,375
God is love, and he who dwells in love dwells in God and God in him.

26
00:02:15,375 --> 00:02:19,287
There is a difference between ghostly things and bodily things.

27
00:02:19,287 --> 00:02:24,087
One ghostly thing dwells in another; but nothing bodily dwells in another.

28
00:02:24,087 --> 00:02:27,575
There may be water in a tub, with the tub round it.

29
00:02:27,575 --> 00:02:30,200
But where the wood is the water is not.

30
00:02:30,200 --> 00:02:33,600
In this sense no material thing dwells in another.

31
00:02:33,600 --> 00:02:48,212
But spiritual things dwell in each other: each several angel with all his joy and happiness is in every other angel as well as in himself, and every angel with all his joy and happiness dwells in me, and God to boot with his entire beatitude, though I discern it not.

32
00:02:48,212 --> 00:03:00,737
If anyone should ask me what God is, I should answer: God is love, and so altogether lovely that creatures all with one accord essay to love his loveliness, whether they do so knowingly or unbeknownst, in joy or sorrow.

33
00:03:00,737 --> 00:03:09,187
Instance the lowest angel in his pure nature: the smallest spark or love-light that ever fell from him would light up the whole world with love and joy.

34
00:03:09,187 --> 00:03:11,150
See his innate perfection!

35
00:03:11,150 --> 00:03:18,975
Moreover, as I have explained at various times, the angels are numerous beyond number.—But to leave love and come to knowledge.

36
00:03:18,975 --> 00:03:22,712
If only we knew God it would be easy to forsake the world.

37
00:03:22,712 --> 00:03:34,637
All that God ever made or shall yet make, all this (I say), if God should give it to my soul without himself, he staying, so to speak, a hair’s-breadth off, would not content my soul nor make me happy.

38
00:03:34,637 --> 00:03:40,250
I am happy when all things are in me and God, and where I am God is, and where God is I am.

39
00:03:40,250 --> 00:03:43,762
He who dwells in love dwells in God and God in him.

40
00:03:43,762 --> 00:03:51,325
Suppose I am in God, then where he is I am; and if God is in me, then, unless the scriptures lie, where I am God is.

41
00:03:51,325 --> 00:03:54,462
It is the absolute truth, as God is God.

42
00:03:54,628 --> 00:04:02,228
Faithful servant, I will set thee over all my goods,’ i.e. the manifold goodness of God in creatures will I set thee over.

43
00:04:02,178 --> 00:04:11,440
Secondly, ‘I will set thee over all my goods’ means: at the source of creature happiness, in the pure unity of God himself wherein he has his own felicity.

44
00:04:11,440 --> 00:04:17,390
In other words: God being the good, in that sense will he set us above his manifold goodness.

45
00:04:17,390 --> 00:04:26,265
Thirdly, he will set us over all his goods, means: above all nameables, all effables, all so-called good things and all intelligibles.

46
00:04:26,265 --> 00:04:29,003
Thus he sets us over all his goods.

47
00:04:29,003 --> 00:04:33,103
Father, I pray thee, make them one as I and thou are one.

48
00:04:33,103 --> 00:04:36,328
Where two grow one, one loses its nature.

49
00:04:36,328 --> 00:04:41,440
Ergo, for God and the soul to be one the soul has to lose her own life and nature.

50
00:04:41,440 --> 00:04:44,015
They are one as regards what is left.

51
00:04:44,015 --> 00:04:49,478
But for them to be one, one must lose its identity and the other must keep its identity.

52
00:04:49,478 --> 00:04:51,053
Then they are the same.

53
00:04:51,053 --> 00:04:56,065
Now, the Holy Ghost says: ‘I pray thee, let them be one as we are one.

54
00:04:56,065 --> 00:04:58,903
I pray thee, make them the same in us.

55
00:04:58,903 --> 00:05:04,315
When I pray for aught my prayer goes for naught; when I pray for naught I pray as I ought.

56
00:05:04,315 --> 00:05:13,490
When I am one with that wherein are all things, past, present and to come, all the same distance and all just the same, then they are all in God and all in me.

57
00:05:13,490 --> 00:05:16,390
There is no thought of Henry or of Conrad.

58
00:05:16,390 --> 00:05:20,940
Praying for aught save God alone is idolatry and unrighteousness.

59
00:05:20,940 --> 00:05:24,140
They pray aright who pray in spirit and in truth.

60
00:05:24,140 --> 00:05:29,028
When praying for someone, for Henry or Conrad, I pray at my weakest.

61
00:05:29,028 --> 00:05:37,940
When praying for no one I pray at my strongest, and when I want nothing and make no request I am praying my best, for in God is no Henry nor no Conrad.

62
00:05:37,940 --> 00:05:44,040
To pray to God for aught save God is wrong and faithless, and, as it were, an imperfection.

63
00:05:44,040 --> 00:05:50,290
For to set up something beside God is, as I lately said, but to make naught of God and God of naught.

64
00:05:50,290 --> 00:06:01,478
Whoso is far and foreign to himself as the chief angel of the Seraphim is far from him, that man owns that same angel just as God does and is God, and that’s the naked truth, as God is God.

65
00:06:01,478 --> 00:06:05,603
God is love, and he that is in love is in God and God in him.

66
00:06:05,603 --> 00:06:08,840
May all of us attain this love whereof I speak.

67
00:06:08,840 --> 00:06:11,653
So help us our Lord Jesus Christ.

68
00:06:11,653 --> 00:06:12,578
Amen.
